name: benefitPartner
description:
The benefitPartner service enables third-party benefit providers to import benefit programs into Workday.  Benefit programs can be announcements or other messages the customer wants the software partner to import into Workday. The program can include a title, description, links, and an image and appears as a card on the worker's home screen.

Example: A wellness week event, Benefits and Pay Hub announcement, or hosted meeting for speaker with a financial or insurance advisor.

name: customObjectDataMultiInstance
description:
The Custom Object Data (Multi-Instance) service enables applications to access and manage multi-instance custom objects.

Custom objects are extensions of existing Workday business objects. Example: The Worker object can be extended to include a custom object named Stock Grants.  If a worker can have more than 1 stock grant, the Stock Grants custom object is a multi-instance custom object. To see the custom object definition in Workday, run the View Custom Object task. You can also run the Custom Object Definitions report  to see all custom object definitions for a business object.

name: customObjectDataSingleInstance
description:
The Custom Object Data (Single-Instance) service enables applications to access and manage single-instance custom objects.

Custom objects are extensions of existing Workday business objects. Example: The Worker object can be extended to include a custom object named Parking Space. If a worker can have only 1 assigned parking space, it is a single-instance custom object. To see the custom object definition in Workday, run the View Custom Object task. You can also run the Custom Object Definitions report  to see all custom object definitions for a business object.

name: customObjectDefinition

name: prismAnalytics
description:
The Workday Public API enables you to programmatically create and manage external data into a
Workday Prism Analytics table. You can load data into a table once or on a regular basis.
You can load data into a table you just created, or an existing table.

For general concepts regarding Workday REST APIs see: [Workday REST API](https://doc.workday.com/admin-guide/en-us/integrations/workday-rest-api/dan1370797985682.html)

See later sections for an overview of tables and buckets.

  CHANGELOG:
  ------------
  New Resources
  ------------
  | V3 Resource | Operations |
  | ------------ | ----------- |
  | dataChanges/{dataChangeID}/validate | GET Validate data change |
  | dataChanges/{dataChangeID}/cancel/{activityID} | POST Cancel data change |

name: timeTracking
description:
The time tracking REST APIs enable you to access time tracking information. These APIs provide the ability to: 
* Enable workers to check in and check out of work and to review and modify their recent check-ins and check-outs. 

* Enable managers to check in and check out of work for a worker.

* View workers who are currently checked in for work.

* Review and modify a worker's check-ins and check-outs. 

* View and create time blocks.

* View time entry validations for a worker.

* View period schedule for a worker.

name: wql
description: The Workday Query Language (WQL) service enables applications to access Workday data using the WQL syntax. It contains resources that define operations to view a summary of data sources, details about a specific data source, business objects, and fields contained within a data source. Information from the response can then be used to construct a WQL request in the Data REST API.
